class Solution {
    public int minAddToMakeValid(String s) {
        int openBrackets = 0;
        int moves = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
            char c = s.charAt(i);
            if (c == '(') {
                openBrackets++;
            } else if (c == ')') {
                if (openBrackets == 0) {
                    moves++;
                } else {
                    openBrackets--;
                }
            }
        }
        return moves;
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:
We iterate through the string character by character. For each character, we check if it is an opening bracket '(' and increment the count of open brackets. If it is a closing bracket ')', we check if there is an opening bracket '(' at the current position. If there is, we decrement the count of open brackets. If there isn't, we increment the moves count. This approach has a time complexity of O(n) where n is the length of the string, and a space complexity of O(1) since we only use a constant amount of space to store the count of open brackets and the moves count. The energy implications are low as we only perform a constant number of operations per character.

